Priorities for early childhood development in low-income countries.

Olusanya BO(1).

Author information:
(1)Maternal and Child Health Unit, Department of Community Health and Primary 
Care, College of Medicine, University of Lagos, Idiaraba, Surulere, Lagos, 
Nigeria. boolusanya@aol.com

The remarkable progress in reducing child mortality in low-income countries is 
now accompanied with a rapidly expanding population of child survivors and 
increased life expectancy. However, many have special health care needs in the 
early foundational years for optimal health and educational and vocational 
status. Investment in early childhood development (ECD) is therefore crucial but 
likely to be constrained by lack of adequate resources making priority-setting 
inevitable. A review of current ECD approaches in sub-Saharan Africa and South 
Asia shows that concerted multidisciplinary and cross-sectoral initiatives 
targeted at children with developmental disabilities across all crucial domains 
