[Life expectancy at birth: impact of variation in mortality by age group and 
cause of death in Campinas, São Paulo State, Brazil].

[Article in Portuguese]

Belon AP(1), Barros MB.

Author information:
(1)Faculdade de Ciências Médicas, Universidade Estadual de Campinas, Brasil. 
paulabelon@gmail.com

This study investigated the impact of variation in mortality by age group and 
cause of death on gains in life expectancy at birth in the city of Campinas, São 
Paulo State, Brazil, in 1991, 2000, and 2005. Life tables were constructed. 
Pollard's method was used to estimate the contributions by age group and cause 
of death on gains in life expectancy. In 1991-2000, the age group that most 
contributed was 0-1 year (31.1% for males and 22.9% for females). In 2000-2005, 
79% of the gain for males was the result of mortality improvements in the 
15-44-year bracket. Cardiovascular diseases made the largest contribution in 
1991-2000 (66.1% for males and 43.5% for females). A loss in longevity was seen 
in men (1.1 year) resulting from increased mortality from external causes. In 
2000-2005, the substantial gain (2.3 year) in male life expectancy was due to a 
reduction in mortality from external causes. Neoplasms had a negative effect on 
the gain (0.11 year for males and 0.15 for females). These findings should help 
support public health policies to reduce mortality risks and increase life 
expectancy.

