Treatment of glioblastoma in "elderly" patients.

Yovino S(1), Grossman SA.

Author information:
(1)The Brain Cancer Program, Sidney Kimmel Comprehensive Cancer Center at Johns 
Hopkins, Orleans Street, Baltimore, MD 21232, USA. sbatkoy2@jhmi.edu

The number of patients over 65 with newly diagnosed glioblastoma is anticipated 
to increase significantly in coming decades as a result of demographic shifts in 
the United States. Older patients with this disease have a significantly worse 
life expectancy compared with patients under 65. Mounting clinical evidence 
suggests that fit elderly patients with glioblastoma benefit from the addition 
of temozolomide to standard surgery and radiation. As a result, for healthy 
patients over 65 we recommend maximal surgical debulking followed by 
involved-field radiotherapy (60 Gy in 30 fractions) with concurrent temozolomide 
(75 mg/m(2)/day) and 6 months of adjuvant temozolomide (150-200 mg/m(2)/day for 
five consecutive days/month). Patients over 65 with newly diagnosed or recurrent 
glioblastoma should also be considered for inclusion in clinical trials. MGMT is 
a validated prognostic marker in patients over 65 and may be useful in clinical 
decision-making in frail elderly patients. Age alone should not be a factor in 
deciding how patients with newly diagnosed glioblastoma should be treated.

